{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487284"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:04:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:04:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"308"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"308","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/308"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.87,0.03,0,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"308"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113108"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"308","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/308"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"308"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95140"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"295"},{"type":"tags","id":"4544"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1172"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3832"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42999"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46532"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46674"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113108"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 25-year-old woman attends the emergency department two hours after the sudden onset of pain in the right lower abdomen. This is associated with nausea, vomiting and faintness. Her last menstrual period ended 6 weeks ago, and she normally has regular 26 day cycles. She is afebrile. Her blood pressure is 100/50 mmHg and the pulse rate is 120/min. She is tender is the right lower abdomen with guarding, rigidity and rebound tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Perforated appendix","Ruptured ectopic pregnancy","Haemorrhagic ovarian cyst","Salpingitis","Ovarian torsion"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture presented in this scenario points to a highly likely diagnosis of a \u003Cstrong\u003Eruptured ectopic pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E. This diagnosis is supported by a history of sudden onset lower abdominal pain, mild hypotension and tachycardia in the context of her last menstrual period being 6 weeks ago. A ruptured ectopic is a diagnosis to consider and cannot be reasonably excluded until a negative b-HCG is returned. This can be investigated with a urinary pregnancy test as a first-line investigation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAppendicitis\u003C/strong\u003E would be an appropriate differential diagnosis for right iliac fossa pain, however most patients would have preceding symptoms of anorexia, fever and generalised abdominal pain prior to it localising to the right iliac fossa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ehaemoarrhagic\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Eovarian cyst\u003C/strong\u003E can present with acute lower abdominal pain in the setting of a negative\u00a0b-HCG.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESalpingitis\u003C/strong\u003E commonly presents as increased abdominal pain, fevers, increased white cell count and a history of unprotected intercourse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOvarian torsion\u003C/strong\u003E is highly possible and urgent review is required. Common symptoms include nausea and vomiting associated with lower abdominal pain. Ovarian torsion is less common than a ruptured ectopic and in this initial assessment of the unstable female to the emergency department, ruptured ectopic needs to be made the first differential diagnosis. The onset of pain in the other conditions would tend to be more gradual in onset.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["\u201cEvery woman of reproductive age is pregnant until proven otherwise\u201d."],"references":["Elson CJ, Salim R, Potdar N, Chetty M, Ross JA, Kirk EJ on behalf of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Diagnosis and management of ectopic pregnancy. BJOG 2016;.123:e15\u2013e55.","Di Saverio, S., Podda, M., De Simone, B. et al. Diagnosis and treatment of acute appendicitis: 2020 update of the WSES Jerusalem guidelines. World J Emerg Surg 15, 27 (2020). https://doi.org/10.1186/s13017-020-00306-3"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95140"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"308"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95140"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-09T18:22:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-09T18:22:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"308"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113108"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups"